03850nam a22006375i 9781978820579DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20212022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021006634  a97819788205797 a10.36019/97819788205792doi  a(DE-B1597)609941  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN2071.I47bR63 2021 4aPN2071.I47bR63 2022 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a792.02/82231 aRogers, Baker A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKing of Hearts :bDrag Kings in the American South /cBaker A. Rogers. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (184 p.) :b13 b-w images, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile drag subcultures have gained mainstream media attention in recent years, the main focus has been on female impersonators. Equally lively, however, is the community of drag kings: cis women, trans men, and non-binary people who perform exaggerated masculine personas onstage under such names as Adonis Black, Papi Chulo, and Oliver Clothesoff. King of Hearts shows how drag king performers are thriving in an unlikely location: Southern Bible Belt states like Tennessee, Georgia, and South Carolina. Based on observations and interviews with sixty Southern drag kings, this study reveals how they are challenging the region’s gender norms while creating a unique community with its own distinctive Southern flair. Reflecting the region’s racial diversity, it profiles not only white drag kings, but also those who are African American, multiracial, and Hispanic. Queer scholar Baker A. Rogers—who has also performed as drag king Macon Love—takes you on an insider’s tour of Southern drag king culture, exploring its history, the communal bonds that unite it, and the controversies that have divided it. King of Hearts offers a groundbreaking look at a subculture that presents a subversion of gender norms while also providing a vital lifeline for non-gender-conforming Southerners.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aDrag kingszSouthern StatesxHistory. 0aGender expressionzSouthern States. 0aMale impersonatorszSouthern StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  adrag kings, LGTBQ, gender, gender studies, women, men, female impersonators, male impersonators, cis women, trans men, non-binary, masculine, personas, Drag Queens, drag, drag performers, American south, southern flair, racial diversity, race, multiracial, queer, drag communities, subculture, gender non-conforming, history of drag, drag king community.40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882057940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978820579423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978820579/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK